04650nam a22006015i 9780226818023DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20222022ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226818023  a(DE-B1597)626496  a(OCoLC)1310343249  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aML200b.C64 2022 7aMUS0000002bisacsh04a780.9747/12231 aCohen, Brigid, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMusical Migration and Imperial New York :bEarly Cold War Scenes /cBrigid Cohen. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (384 p.) :b19 halftones, 1 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNew Material Histories of Music00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tIntroduction: A Recent History of Music, Citizenship, and American Empire -- t1. Third Space, Scene of Subjection -- t2 Cold War Acropolis I -- t3. Cold War Acropolis II -- t4. A Counter- Discourse of Orientalism -- t5. The Haunting of Empires -- t6. Concluding Thoughts -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tArchival Sources -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThrough archival work and storytelling, Musical Migration and Imperial New York revises many inherited narratives about experimental music and art in postwar New York. From the urban street level of music clubs and arts institutions to the world-making routes of global migration and exchange, this book redraws the map of experimental art to reveal the imperial dynamics and citizenship struggles that continue to shape music in the United States. Beginning with the material conditions of power that structured the cityscape of New York in the early Cold War years, Brigid Cohen looks at a wide range of artistic practices (concert music, electronic music, jazz, performance art) and actors (Edgard Varèse, Charles Mingus, Yoko Ono, and Fluxus founder George Maciunas) as they experimented with new modes of creativity. Cohen links them with other migrant creators vital to the city’s postwar culture boom, creators whose stories have seldom been told (Halim El-Dabh, Michiko Toyama, Vladimir Ussachevsky). She also gives sustained and serious treatment to the work of Yoko Ono, something long overdue in music scholarship. Musical Migration and Imperial New York is indispensable reading, offering a new understanding of global avant-gardes and American experimental music as well as the contrasting feelings of belonging and exclusion on which they were built.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aAvant-garde (Music)zNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy20th century. 0aMusiczNew York (State)zNew Yorky20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh  aart, avant-garde, citizenship, Cold War, empire, experimentalism, migration, music, New York, United States.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts 2022z9783110992809oZDB-23-DPK08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2022 Englishz978311099281608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076650940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226818023423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226818023/original  a978-3-11-076650-9  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  a978-3-11-099281-6  EBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2022 Englishb2022  a978-3-11-099389-9  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishb2022 